1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
 So now we're going to take a look inside of a generic edit view, and we want to look at how it functions internally so that we can override and extend some of those functions.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:15,000
 So we can take the generic edit view and turn it into an edit view that supports an owned row.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:19,000
 So this is a review, we've gone back a couple of lectures.

4
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 This is the edit form flow, right, and I went through this in great and gory detail, so I'll just review it really quickly, right?

5
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:30,000
 So you're going, you've hit the edit button, right?

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:34,000
 So you do a get request to like /1 or /15.

7
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:37,000
 You're going to grab that data, oops.

8
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 You're going to go in, you're going to load the primary key 1 or 2 or 15.

9
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,000
 If you didn't find it, you're going to send in 404 error, and then you're going to fill the form with old data.

10
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 The user is going to edit that data, they're going to post the good data.

11
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 Then the form is going to be validated, of course, according to the form rules.

12
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,000
 Remember, the model kind of deals with the back end, and the form kind of deals with the front end.

13
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:11,000
 So the validation is a form aspect, and then if there's an error, it goes back and allows you to redo it.

14
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:18,000
 And then if there's no error in the submitted data, then we load a new model up, we reload the model,

15
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 check to see if that model is accessible, and accessible is going to matter to a lot to us in a second.

16
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:31,000
 If it's there and you can read it, and you're legally allowed to read it, great, otherwise we're going to give you a 404.

17
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:39,000
 As you're submitting the data, and that has to do with if they messed with the form or something, or they're submitting it to the wrong URL.

18
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:45,000
 But if we can get the data, we change the data, and we store the updated data, and then we do the success URL, right?

19
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:52,000
 So that's the basic form flow, we did that before, we did that with every one of our cruds.

20
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 And we also looked at this documentation in the generic list view, it could be in some of the edit views.

21
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:09,000
 At some point you will see in the Django documentation, it's telling you how this class is functioning internally.

22
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 How it's working its own magic inside itself, and this is method flow chart.

23
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 First it's going to call setup, then it's called dispatch, check to see if the method's allowed.

24
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:28,000
 Get its template name, get a query set, load the data from the database, get the context object name, get the context data, and then render to response.

25
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 And so you might say, why are they showing us all this?

26
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 And the answer is because we can get our hands in and mess with these things.

27
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 These are like our access points into this generic list view class that allow us to dig in and make changes.

28
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 And so if we were to look at that same picture and think of it from the point of view of which methods are being called

29
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:00,000
 at the moment where this generic edit, in this case it's going to be an edit view, this generic edit view is happening.

30
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,000
 So here we go.

31
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 So the get request comes in, it's got some primary key, so it does a get query set.

32
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:11,000
 And it reads this thing, and then it reads it using get query set.

33
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 It's still reading it, but it happens to be doing it in a method called get query set.

34
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 And if get query set works, or doesn't, then it keeps on going.

35
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:27,000
 Then as it's rendering the template, it's going to get the context data by calling a method called get context data.

36
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 That's another place that we're going to play with.

37
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:34,000
 We're going to inject ourselves into get context data.

38
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 Then we'll do the edit, the post will come in, and then it's going to do validation, but it does it in a method called form valid.

39
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:48,000
 So the first thing that happens upon the receipt of post is it checks to see if the form is valid.

40
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 We are going to add our own little code into form valid as well.

41
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 If it goes back, it does a render, so it's going to use get context data.

42
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:03,000
 If it is good, there's no error, then it's going to actually call get query set again to get the data.

43
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 And then it's going to modify the data, and then it's going to store the data.

44
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 There's some name for this, but I didn't put it in.

45
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 The point is, each of these moments where there's something critical going on,

46
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:20,000
 form valid get query set, that's a place where we can extend the behavior of this built in class

47
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 without knowing too much about the class.

48
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 And I showed you at the end of a few lectures ago this crazy override.

49
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 I did this crazy, crazy override where I made this weird equine view,

50
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:44,000
 and I have a model of car and a template name, and then I'm overriding get query set.

51
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 So this is extending generic list view, but instead of using the get query set that's in generic list view,

52
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 we're going to call our own get query set, so instead of reading car objects, we're going to read horse objects.

53
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:01,000
 And then we're going to return a list of them, and that's what the get query set has to do.

54
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 The rule of get query set is you get called, you have to return a list.

55
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:09,000
 If we didn't write this code, it would do this except with car, but we did write this code.

56
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 Why? Because we wanted to override it.

57
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 Was there any logic to it? No, just because I wanted to show you crazy things, right?

58
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 And so because I've overridden in the generic list view, it's not calling the generic list views query set at all,

59
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 which would look at the model car, but instead it's calling mine that's in wacky equine view.

60
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 And so when it prints out, you see a list of horses, not a list of cars,

61
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:46,000
 because I overrode what behavior was inside the list view class, which normally would be informed by that,

62
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 but my code in here ignored it.

63
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 Again, I have no purpose for this other than showing you that I can change the behavior of the parent class

64
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 while creating a derived class.

65
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 Now sometimes, in this case, I'm just completely overriding it, and it's like,

66
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,000
 I don't care what you were going to do before, I'm going to do something completely different.

67
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 And you have to know what the rules are, I had to know what the return.

68
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 It took me a while to write this, and I might have even looked at some Django source code to figure this out.

69
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:18,000
 But eventually, through Stack Overflow, I figured this out.

70
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 So this is not trivial to write, and I'm not expecting you to write this.

71
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 I just want to show you the technique, like this keyword args, that's something.

72
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 I'm sure at some point I knew what it was, but I just stole that off of Stack Overflow, like everybody does.

73
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:46,000
 So, in this def get query set, you'll see that I have just overridden and ignored the def query set from generic list view, okay?

74
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:50,000
 That's one way of overriding a method.

75
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:54,000
 Another way of overriding a method is this get context data.

76
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 So what is get context data going to do?

77
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 Well, at some level, get context data is what puts in this crazy, this list, ends up going into horse list, right?

78
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 So that's somehow this variable that I return here in query set ends up being put into my context is horse list.

79
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 So then I can write this loop that prints that stuff out.

80
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 And that's by convention, right?

81
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 It actually looks at the type of this thing and says, oh, that's a list of horses.

82
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:27,000
 So it makes up the variable and puts it in the context.

83
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 Now where that's being done in generic list view is in a method called get context data.

84
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 And so I actually don't want to completely replace get context data, although I probably could if I want because this is so simple.

85
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 What I actually want to do is I want to augment the context and I want to throw something else in it.

86
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:54,000
 So what I want to do is I want to run the code from generic list view first.

87
00:07:54,000 --> 00:08:03,000
 I want to get the context back from that and then I want to add something to it and then return sort of like this composite context, okay?

88
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 And it's not, the syntax is a little scary, but it's okay.

89
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:12,000
 So let's take a look at get context data.

90
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 Just like anything, self is the instance, self is always the instance.

91
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 KW args is just a way of taking all the parameters so I can pass them in.

92
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:25,000
 So what I'm going to say is I'm going to say, hey, super.

93
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 Super is like calling get context data in generic list view.

94
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 So go into my super class, wacky equines view is a subclass, list view is my super class.

95
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 Super, get context data and pass whatever arguments were going in there.

96
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 We're all good.

97
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 So just call that, do it and pass in all the arguments and do whatever.

98
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 And that's what ends up putting in horse list.

99
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:54,000
 And so at that point, context is going to be a dictionary that has horse list in it.

100
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 But then I want to put some more stuff in.

101
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 So then that goes into generic list view and then comes back out of generic list view and gives me.

102
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 And if all I did is return to context, then I really wouldn't have changed anything.

103
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:12,000
 But what I'm going to do is I'm going to throw in this little extra key called crazy thing and put the string crazy thing in it.

104
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 And then I return all that.

105
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:19,000
 And then eventually it goes into the template and this context finds its way into the template.

106
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:22,000
 And again, that's all inside of generic list view.

107
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 And eventually horse list is there because of the call to the super.

108
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 And crazy thing is there just because I explicitly put it in.

109
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 And so I have augmented without replacing.

110
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 The first one I completely replaced get query set.

111
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 And the second one I called the parent.

112
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:50,000
 And then I augmented the return value and then returned kind of the combination of what the list view did and what I want to add to the list view.

113
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:59,000
 So we're going to use both of these techniques coming up when we start talking about the owner list, the owner.py code.

114
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:05,000
 And how we can then jack in to this generic code and implement our owner field.

115
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 So that's the next thing that we're going to do.

